It comes after a study showed cheaper farmland and proximity to 
population centres are fuelling growth in Amish colonies in New York.

The Amish, many of them from Ohio or Pennsylvania, have set up 10 new 
settlements in New York since 2010 - growth that doubles other states.

That population has grown by nearly a third in two years, to 13,000. As 
recently as 1991, there were just 3,900 Amish in the state.

The first New York Amish districts were established in the Conewango 
Valley in 1949, but in-migration slowed until about 10 years ago.

Pennsylvania had the nation's largest Amish population in the new survey, at just over 61,000, and New York was fifth.

